Paper Reviewed: Investing with Cryptocurrencies -- evaluating their potential for portfolio allocation strategies¶

According to the authors, they present the broadest study on investing with cryptocurrencies (CCs) conducted so far. They calculate out-of-sample performance and diversification benefits for the most prevalent portfolio construction methods, including mean-variance optimization, risk-parity, and maximumdiversification strategies, as well as combined strategies.

  • Literature Highlights of CC investments:

    • remarkably high average realized returns and and correspondingly high risk and uncertainty.
    • high volatility; also there are unfavorable properties in CC investments, e.g., frequent pricing bubbles, accumulation of jumps and even evidence of price manipulation
    • low correlations of CC returns with those of traditional financial assets and other CCs -> potential diversification effects
    • returns of CCs have even heavier tails as compared to those of equities

  • Findings:

    • CCs can improve the risk-return profile of portfolios, but their benefit depends on investor objectives.
    • CCs contribute to diversification.
    • Illiquidity of CCs hurts out-of-sample performance, however, their diversification benefits persist.

  • Data used in the paper:

    • over the period 2015-01-01 to 2019-12-31
    • focus on solid CCs and also sidestep ICOs: excluding coins that did not already circulate in January 2015, went extinct before December 2019, or have only patchy price series

  • Methodology highlights:
    • 9 asset allocation models (table above)
    • rule out short selling, a standard assumption in CCs.
    • performance metrics:
      • cumulative wealth
      • Sharpe ratio
      • certainty equivalent
      • adjusted Sharpe ratio (mitigate the drawback of normality assumption for returns)
      • portfolio turnover
      • target turnover
    • diversification metrics:
      • portfolio diversification index
      • effective N
      • diversification ratio

Quick Replication (with Extensional Analytics)¶

I managed to replicate the major part of this well-rounded, broad study on asset allocation with cryptocurrencies (CCs) using Yahoo Finance's public available data in the last two days. The results show that crptocurrencies have potential to increase the risk-adjusted return of portfolios (see finding_summary.xlsx). Specifically, as shown in the summary worksheet, top performers in terms of various metrics are among portfolios that include CCs, e.g., MD, ERC. Also, according to diversification-related metrics, the diversification effect of CCs as claimed in the original paper are found predominantly among risk-oriented strategies. The best strategy in the below out-of-sample test would be the one relying on Maximum Diversification (i.e., MD (wiht CCs)).

# util functions for performance/reporting
def plot_cumu_rets(ret_data, title):
    fig, ax = plt.subplots()
    dtFmt = mdates.DateFormatter('%Y-%b') # define the formatting
    ret_data.plot(ax=ax)
    plt.gca().xaxis.set_major_formatter(dtFmt) 
    plt.gca().xaxis.set_major_locator(mdates.MonthLocator(interval=6))
    plt.minorticks_off()
    #portfolio_wt_ccs_cumu_rets[["EW","RR-MaxRet"]].plot(ax=ax, secondary_y=True)
    plt.title(title)
    plt.show()

def combine_metrics(df_wo_ccs, df_wt_ccs, reindex=True):
    df1, df2 = df_wo_ccs.copy(), df_wt_ccs.copy()
    df1.index = [tag + " (Without CCs)" for tag in df1.index]
    df2.index = [(tag + " (With CCs)" if tag != "^OEX" else tag + " (S&P100)") for tag in df2.index]
    res = pd.concat([df1,df2])
    if reindex:
        tmp_index = list(res.index)
        new_index = [tmp_index[-1],]+tmp_index[0:-1]
        res = res.loc[new_index]
    return res
